<h1>@HI{{hazu}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}
<li> @Vnai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no}} @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}} which indicates the speaker's belief that something will happen (or happened).
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come}}ru @EM{{hazu}}desuyo. kinou @KJ{{electricity^tale}}ga arimashitakara.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm sure he'll come. I received a phone call from him yesterday.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}} indicates an expectation based on some reliable knowledge and so it is more than
just a guess.
</p>

<p>
An expectation that something will not be the case can be expressed either by negating the sentence before @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}
or by following  the sentence with @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}} @HI{{ha/ga nai}}. The latter construction carries heavier weight.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}} behaves as a noun so if "S @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}" is a relative clause, @HI{{no}} follows it.
</p>

